        \begin{minipage}[T]{.95\textwidth}
          \parbox[t][\columnheight]{\textwidth}
            {
    \begin{block}{Introduction}

    Currently, there are no reliable method of comparing estimated means copies per partitions ($\lambda$). An approach based on the confidence intervals~\shortcite{dube_mathematical_2008} fails during multiple comparisions, because of the decline of the coverage probability. On the other hand, methods based on the uncertainty~\shortcite{bhat_single_2009} do not take into account number of repetitions. We propose a novel method, as part of our \emph{dpcR} package \cite{burdukiewicz_2014}, for comparing results of dPCR experiments using rigorous statistical approach. 

    
    \end{block}
    
    \vfill
            
     \begin{block}{Test scheme}

    Generalized Linear Models (GLM) are linear models for data, where response variable has non-normal distributions (as binomially distributed positive partitions in digital PCR experiments). We propose a linear model reflecting relationships in results of digital PCR:

    \begin{equation}
    \log{Y} = \beta^T X
    \end{equation}
    
    where $Y$ are counts, $X$ are experiments names (categorical data) and $\beta$ are linear model coefficients for every experiment. Moreover, $\exp{\beta} = \lambda$.
    
    \hskip 0.5cm
     
    Estimated means copies per partitions obtained from the model are compared each other using multiple t-test~\shortcite{bretz_2010}.
    
    \hskip 0.5cm
    \end{block}
    \vfill   
    
    \begin{block}{Restrictions}
    The linear model above can be used only when the concentration of template molecules in sample is small (positive partitions contain very rarely more than 1 template particle). In situation when partitions are more saturated with template molecules, binomial regression is more precise.
    
    \end{block}
    \vfill    
    
    \begin{block}{Sample reaction}
    Ten array dPCR experiments (765 partitions) were generated. First five have from 9 to 11 molecules in a single array. Last five experiments have from 55 to 65 molecules. All experiments were compared using the proposed framework.
    \end{block}
    \vfill 
    
    
